description:
From GoogleGroups:

I know there's been a lot of work on the way connections are handled in 
1.3, but what used to work in the beta 2 release and prior no longer works 
in the RC... Is this broken now?

{code:php}
<?php
$mongo_one_connection = new Mongo('mongodb://[SERVER_ONE]:27017');
$mongo_one_db = $mongo_one_connection->selectDB('mongo_test_one');
$mongo_one_collection = new MongoCollection($mongo_one_db, 'collection_one');

$mongo_two_connection = new Mongo('mongodb://[SERVER_TWO]:27017');
$mongo_two_db = $mongo_two_connection->selectDB('mongo_test_two');
$mongo_two_collection = new MongoCollection($mongo_two_db, 'collection_two');

$record['date'] = time();

$mongo_two_collection->insert($record);
{code}

So what happens here is that a collection named 'collection_two' gets 
created in a database named 'mongo_test_two' on SERVER_ONE, where I'd have 
expected it to be on SERVER_TWO.

If both connections use the same db name, eg. 'mongo_test', the insert 
happens on the proper server.

And for clarity, these are two separate servers and not members of the the 
same replica set.

This following script:

{code}
<?php
$m = new Mongo( 'mongodb://user:user@whisky:27017/test' );
$collection = $m->demo->collection;

foreach ( $m->getConnections() as $c )
{
    echo $c['hash'], "\n";
}
?>
{code}

Throws either valgrind errors, or crashes.

I'm doing queries on a property 'ts' that is put on objects as a large integer. (milliseconds since 1970).

The following query:

$query = array(
	"ts" => array(
		'$gt' => 1352972258267,
	)
);

will return entries that have 'ts' properies lower than the criteria.

I have two machines connected to the same db. The db runs on the 64 bit machine. Only the 64bit machine is affected by this bug. The 32bit machine returns the correct results (strange to me that it is not the opposite).

The machine affected is like this:
Linux uwap.uninett.no 2.6.32-5-amd64 #1 SMP Sun May 6 04:00:17 UTC 2012 x86_64 GNU/Linux


In my app, I've done this quick fix:

$query = array(
	"ts" => array(
		'$gt' => new MongoInt64("1352972258267"),
	)
);

This works on both the 32bit and the 64bit machine.

On the mongodb shell, the initial query is working as expected on both 64bit and 32bit machine.

When instantiating Mongo and passing a non-existent host, the driver doesn't throw an exception, but just ignores the host and connects to localhost.

{code:title=test.php}
<?php

$mongo = new Mongo('non existent host');
//connected to localhost :/
$db = $mongo->selectDB('some_local_db');
$data = $db->collection->count();
{code}

Segfault occurs on some of the queries. This only occurs on one of our batch scripts, probably specific to some query with very long conditions.

